<p><strong>Asking To Meet Someone 1-1</strong></p>

<p>Since relationships are built through 1-1 interactions, you canâ€™t build meaningful relationships without 1-1 meetings. There are tons of things you can do to make a meeting great before it even starts.</p>

<p>Scheduling. Here are some tactical doâ€™s and do notâ€™s that make scheduling simple.</p>

<p><em>Do:</em> <strong>Say what you want to talk about during the meeting in the email.</strong> It makes it easy for them to say yes and it gives you both a little reminder when you go back and check the email right before the meeting.</p>

<p><em>Donâ€™t:</em> Use the term â€œIâ€™d like to pick your brain about â€¦â€ It screams â€œIâ€™m not willing to do the legwork to come up with specific questions and topics.â€</p>

<p><em>Do:</em> <strong>Give as much information as possible</strong> - â€œIâ€™m based in the Mission and Iâ€™m in SOMA on Thursday afternoons.â€</p>

<p><em>Donâ€™t:</em> Be vague or pretend to be busy when youâ€™re not. One of my favorite lines to avoid vagueness is: â€œIâ€™m flexible on time and place but like to offer a concrete suggestionâ€¦â€</p>

<p><em>Do:</em> <strong>Anchor the conversation with 2-3 options around both time and place.</strong> Windows of time are totally fine. â€œWould you like to meet over coffee at Stable Cafe between 2-4pm on Thursday or Friday?â€</p>

<p><em>Donâ€™t:</em> Ask â€œwhen is best for you?â€ or say â€œwe should grab coffee!â€ without an anchor time. It seems nice because you give them all the choice, but youâ€™re also putting all the work on their desk and gives them no information about your preferences.</p>

<p><strong>Calendar Invite</strong> It might seem obvious, but many people still screw up the concluding act leading up to a meeting - a calendar event. Busy folks live by their calendars, so make it easy for them to remember the meeting - where/when itâ€™s happening, who itâ€™s with, and possibly what itâ€™s about. Hereâ€™s a little sample from my calendar:
It could be even better if I had titled it â€œBen- Jim discuss AI Strategiesâ€ or put the subject in the notes section.</p>

<p><strong>Research</strong> Do your homework before a meeting. Stalk your counterpart on the internet a bit. Read their twitter/blog, skim their LinkedIn, Github, what have you. The whole goal is to understand a bit more about who they are, what theyâ€™ve done, and what excites them. Itâ€™s also just flattering when someone pulls out a relevant reference to your web page in a conversation.</p>

