<p><strong>Content</strong></p>

<p>Nobody has much time to go through everything they get in their mailbox.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Smart Subject Line</strong> Make your subject line smart enough to be opened by the reader.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Call To Action At The Top</strong> If you must send a long email with a lot of information, put the call to action up at the top. Something like: â€œIâ€™m sending this email to see if you can attend the event below. Just respond with a â€˜Yesâ€™ or â€˜Noâ€™.â€</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>It is very important to know who you are writing the email. An impersonal, vague, bland email wonâ€™t get you very far. You need to do your homework very well. It helps you create good context in your email and make the email copy engaging also. It gives a very good message in the mind of receiver. It lets them understand that you are genuinely reaching out to him/her with a good context which could add value to you.</p>

<p>Just tell me three things.</p>

<p><strong>First, in a matter of fact way tell what it is you are doing.</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Your first 3 lines should give quick overview of Who you are? Why you are writing? No buzzwords, just an explanation. â€œA world changing next generation platform for GenZ blah blah blahâ€ - yuck. â€œWeâ€™re making an app for ordering pizza. Itâ€™s better than all the other apps out there because itâ€™s like Kayak - it meta-searches all the local pizza places near you to give you a list of prices for the options youâ€™ve selectedâ€ - yay.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Introduce yourself, but donâ€™t make a meal of it. For example, I put my personal details in brackets like this in a recent pitch: (Iâ€™m a Zen master, psychotherapist, and published author.)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Alternatively, Do some discrete name dropping. Instead of saying, â€œMy guest post was recently published at SevenSands.comâ€ you could say, John MacDonald recently asked me to write a guest post at SevenSands.com and it was well received by his readers.â€</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Briefly list previous gigs. You want to make sure that your recipient knows that he or she is in good company. Which well-known blogs have you been published in? Which relevant jobs have you held down?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The best way to figure that out is to see whether youâ€™ve done something awesome in the past, something that indicates that youâ€™ll be doing awesome things in the future. I often check peopleâ€™s LinkedIn profiles through Rapportive when they email me â€“ Iâ€™ll see where theyâ€™re working, where they went to school, and what their deal is. For example, Iâ€™ve learned that people who are currently working in finance but thinking about â€œstarting their own startupâ€ are almost always a red flag. (No offense to finance itself, I studied finance.) Going to a good school is a plus. Working at a startup Iâ€™ve heard of is a plus. Being a consultant or running a small company is usually a minus.If you donâ€™t have anything yet in terms of experience, then put together a good looking website (not a deck) that makes it look like you put some real thought into what youâ€™re trying to do</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Tell how you think they can help.</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>â€œYour vision with Wikipedia inspired us to contact you and weâ€™d love to work with youâ€ - doesnâ€™t tell me what you want from me - yuck. â€œWeâ€™d love to bring you on as a board member. We have an angel investor lined up, but she feels we need someone experienced in consumer internet on our board. Also, we need introductions to venture capitalists and weâ€™ve targeted 10 major pizza chains who weâ€™d like to work with and we think you could help us get meetings at a higher level in those organizations.â€ - yay, maybe I can help with that.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Nothing drives people crazier than an email where someone sends over a lot of information but doesnâ€™t say what theyâ€™d like you to do. I often respond to those immediately by asking: What do you want me to do? Do you want me introduce you to someone? Do you want me to read your blog post and give you feedback? Do you want me to respond with whether Iâ€™ll be able to attend an event? Be clear and say it explicitly up front.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Say what drew you to them in the first place. Be specific and name an article that made a difference to you. Again, be honest. Donâ€™t say you like something, just to please. Here is an example. In a recent pitch I wrote
      * The reason why Iâ€™m so excited about reading your work is because:
          1. You write because you want to write.
          2. You write what you want to write about.
          3. You write with both depth and elegance</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Be reasonable with your request. Last 2 lines should be focused on What is the final action you want from your reader?</p>
    <ul>
      <li>â€œPlease donâ€™t tell me to go to your startupâ€™s website and give you feedback. To actually give your product or website a thorough review and analyze it in a way that is useful actually takes a lot of work. â€œ</li>
      <li>If I can respond to something in less than two minutes, Iâ€™ll do it immediately. What do you want feedback on? The business model? The color of your button? The text? Be specific and reasonable. If you want someoneâ€™s feedback on something, be concrete and ask a specific question that can be answered in a few minutes.Please donâ€™t expect the reader to do the work to figure out what you want them to do. I consider that lazy. Donâ€™t ask â€œWhat do you think we could do to get more customers?â€
        <ul>
          <li>Hereâ€™s an example of one of the bigger tasks people often ask me to do for them:</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  <p>Hi Mattan,</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>(redacted) here. You donâ€™t know me, but your post on getting accepted to YC fired me up just now.</p>
