<p><strong>How It Benefits Them</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Show me why I should take the time to help you Iâ€™m very very active in my charity work, but your startup is not a charity. (If it is, then omit this last oneâ€¦ but Iâ€™m already advising too many so I probably canâ€™t take on more right now!) :-) â€œWe thought youâ€™d enjoy meeting young entrepreneursâ€ - bzzzzt. I DO enjoy meeting young entrepreneurs, I do it all the time as a matter of routine at conferences and through friends and so on. But if youâ€™d like more than a friendly pat on the back and encouragement, then treat me like a businessperson - letâ€™s find something thatâ€™s mutually agreeable. â€œIf you could join us as an advisor, weâ€™d be able to compensate you with stock options in a quantity appropriate to our stage of development.â€ - yay.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Research the other person. If you are a blogger wanting to land a guest post, study the â€˜Aboutâ€™ page and read many of his or her blog articles. The same goes for wanting a job. What are they interested in? What topic might be of interest to them? What is their passion at the moment?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Focus on how you can help the person you are writing to. Are they going on holiday and might need guest posts? Are they expanding their business and might need new staff members? Would their blog benefit from your proposed theme? Have they written a book that you could promote?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>State whatâ€™s in it for them. Why might they like to offer you a guest post, article, or job? Sometimes itâ€™s difficult to find something to say. Here are two recent examples: â€œIâ€™m sure this will be a very useful article. It will provide a roadmap to a happier life for your readers.â€ In one instance, I didnâ€™t know what to say. So I said: â€œWhatâ€™s in it for you? Well, maybe just the sheer thrill of it!â€ It worked!</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>A free sample of your product, or a 15 minute call to learn more about how you can help them, are not valuable to the people you want to network with. Theyâ€™re busy and they donâ€™t need discounts, so both of these are totally wrong.</p>

<p>Instead, ask yourself:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Is there something youâ€™re good at (for example, design or conversion optimization) that they might not be experts at, and can you offer them free help on their site or a side project?</li>
  <li>Can you send them ideas for improving their business that they havenâ€™t thought of? James Altucher (http://www.jamesaltucher.com/2014/05/the-ultimate-guide-for-becoming-an-idea-machine/) comes up with 10 ideas a day, and when he was getting started would often send them to companies for free. Thatâ€™s how he landed many of his paying clients.</li>
  <li>Are there people that you know that the person in question would like to meet? Can you make a warm introduction?</li>
  <li>Are there books or products (not yours) that the person could get a lot of value from? Noah Kagan (https://twitter.com/noahkagan), a master networker, used to send people Ex-Officio underwear.</li>
</ul>

